faq:
  - q: "What is ATS and how does it filter resumes?"
    a: "ATS stands for Applicant Tracking System — the software used by over 95% of Fortune 500 companies and most mid-size employers to manage job applications. ATS systems scan resumes for keyword relevance, parse formatting to extract structured data, and rank or filter candidates before any human reviews the application. Approximately 75% of resumes are rejected by ATS before a recruiter sees them — often due to formatting issues, missing keywords, or parsing failures rather than lack of qualification."
  - q: "How do I know if my resume is ATS-compatible?"
    a: "Paste your resume into a plain text editor (Notepad, TextEdit). If the content is readable, logically ordered, and all formatting survived, your resume is likely ATS-compatible. If columns collapse, text boxes become garbled, or headers disappear, your resume has ATS compatibility issues. Key failure signals: tables, text boxes, headers and footers with key information, graphics, and non-standard section names."
  - q: "What are the most common ATS failures?"
    a: "The 12 most common ATS failures are: (1) Tables and columns that collapse on parsing. (2) Text boxes with key information. (3) Contact info in headers or footers. (4) Non-standard section headers. (5) Graphics, logos, or images. (6) Missing keywords from the job description. (7) Uncommon fonts below 10pt. (8) PDF format when DOCX is preferred. (9) Keyword synonyms instead of exact job-description language. (10) No location field. (11) Dates in unusual formats. (12) Skills buried in descriptions instead of a dedicated Skills section."
  - q: "What keywords should my resume include?"
    a: "Your resume should include the specific keywords from the job description — not synonyms or paraphrases. Extract the 10–12 most important skills, tools, and requirements from the job posting. Check your resume for each one. ATS systems parse exact matches and near-matches but treat synonyms as misses. 'Machine learning' and 'ML' may be treated as different terms. 'Python' and 'Python programming' may also differ."
  - q: "Does a fancy resume template hurt my ATS score?"
    a: "Almost certainly yes. Resume templates with columns, sidebars, icons, progress bars, and graphics are ATS disasters. They look impressive to the human eye and fail at the parsing stage — meaning no human ever sees them. Use single-column, text-based formats. Your content is the differentiator, not your template design."
  - q: "Should I submit my resume as PDF or Word (DOCX)?"
    a: "Check the job application instructions first — some systems specify a preference. If no preference is stated: DOCX is more reliably parsed by older ATS systems. PDF preserves formatting and is preferred for roles where a human will definitely read it. For applications to large companies using enterprise ATS (Workday, Taleo, iCIMS, Greenhouse), DOCX is generally safer. Keep both versions ready."
